05169nam a22008895i 9780231552394DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020034504  a97802315523947 a10.7312/katz197882doi  a(DE-B1597)566429  a(OCoLC)1202459286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJA71 4aJA71 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a301.01qLOC1 aKatznelson, Ira, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDesolation and Enlightenment :bPolitical Knowledge After Total War, Totalitarianism, and the Holocaust /cIra Katznelson. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tOne: Beyond the Common Measure -- tTwo: The Origins of Dark Times -- tThree: A Seminar on the State -- tFour: A New Objectivity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring and especially after World War II, a group of leading scholars who had been perilously close to the war’s devastation joined others fortunate enough to have been protected by distance in an effort to redefine and reinvigorate liberal ideals for a radically new age. Treating evil as an analytical category, they sought to discover the sources of twentieth-century horror and the potentialities of the modern state in the wake of desolation. In the process, they devised strikingly new ways to understand politics, sociology, and history that reverberate still.In this major intellectual history, Ira Katznelson examines the works of Hannah Arendt, Robert Dahl, Richard Hofstadter, Harold Lasswell, Charles Lindblom, Karl Polanyi, and David Truman, detailing their engagement with the larger project of reclaiming the West’s moral bearing. In light of their epoch’s calamities, these intellectuals insisted that the tradition of Enlightenment thought required a new realism, a good deal of renovation, and much recommitment. This array of historians, political philosophers, and social scientists understood that a simple reassertion of liberal modernism had been made radically insufficient by the enormities and moral catastrophes of war, totalitarianism, and the Holocaust. Confronting dashed hopes for reason and knowledge, they asked not just whether the Enlightenment should define modernity but also which Enlightenment we should wish to have.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aHuman behaviorxPhilosophy. 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 0aJewsxPublic opinionxHistory. 0aPolitical psychology. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPolitical sociology 0aPolitical sociology. 0aTotal war. 0aWar (Philosophy) 0aWar (Philosophy). 0aWorld politicsy1945-1989. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/katz1978840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231552394/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-071